We are a university student team working on a fictional business-process-and-software project about a struggling space tourism company run by “Elon Bezos”.
Overall project context
The company has major business problems:
	• health-related flight cancellations
	• poor payment behavior from customers
	• bad reviews and weak customer satisfaction
	• high logistical and maintenance costs
The course goal is to improve business processes and design a software-supported solution.
However, our team is responsible for only one part of the overall company process:
Our team scope
We are responsible only for the “Space Flight” phase.
We are not building the whole company system.
Other teams handle other phases.
So our job is to:
	• analyze the Space Flight process
	• define relevant personas for this phase
	• identify major problems and exceptions in this phase
	• design a better target process
	• build a small but runnable proof of concept focused on one core process inside the Space Flight phase
Professor’s expectations
The professor wants:
	• a runnable Java program
	• clear process thinking, not just code
	• strong documentation
	• a realistic and focused prototype
	• proper consideration of exceptions, not only the happy path
	• compliance with software engineering principles, especially:
		○ SOLID
		○ DRY
		○ KISS
		○ YAGNI
Allowed third-party components:
	• JavaFX
	• Logging framework
	• JDBC connector
	• JUnit
Important grading criteria
Development
	• runnable program
	• technical documentation with architecture and program logic
	• syntactically correct diagrams with appropriate detail
	• clean code
	• SOLID-compliant design
	• understandable structure
	• maintainable implementation
Process design and documentation
	• clear problem analysis
	• clear business value
	• personas for all active user groups in the core process
	• BPMN diagrams with correct syntax
	• enough detail in the core process
	• special focus on exception cases
	• clear scope description
	• clear separation between implemented features and mocked features
	• UI mockups / understandable interface visualization
	• user manual
Final presentation
	• coherent storyline from problem to solution to prototype
	• clear explanation of personas and addressed problems
	• explanation of process and data exchange between roles and systems
	• clear value proposition and differentiating points
	• lessons learned during the project
	• all team members participate
Feedback from professor we must address
The professor specifically challenged us to think beyond the simple happy path.
Important feedback included:
	• consider drag-and-drop meaningfully
	• consider exception cases
	• think about what happens if support is unavailable or incapacitated
	• think in at least two cases, not only one normal flow
So our software and process design must explicitly include:
	1. a normal support case
	2. an emergency or fallback case
Recommended focus for our prototype
Our proof of concept should focus on:
In-Flight Passenger Support and Emergency Escalation
This means:
during the actual space flight, passengers may feel fear, nausea, stress, discomfort, or more serious health problems.
The company needs software support so onboard support staff and base-station staff can react in a structured way.
Core personas in our phase (you can add more or adjust it to make it more plausible)
	1. Passenger
		○ the customer on the flight
		○ may report discomfort or need support
	2. Onboard Support
		○ responsible for passenger well-being during the flight
		○ handles normal incidents
	3. Base Station Operator
		○ remote backup / supervisory role
		○ takes over escalated or emergency cases
Two main scenarios we must support
Scenario 1: Normal support case
	• passenger feels unwell, anxious, or mildly stressed
	• onboard support reviews the case
	• support chooses an action
	• the passenger is monitored
	• the case is resolved
Scenario 2: Emergency / fallback case
	• passenger has a severe issue OR onboard support becomes unavailable
	• the incident is escalated to base station
	• emergency workflow starts
	• all actions are logged
	• the case remains traceable and visible
What the software prototype should do
The prototype should be a small JavaFX desktop application that supports this core process.
It should include:
	• passenger overview
	• incident creation
	• incident categorization by severity
	• normal support handling
	• emergency escalation
	• action/history logging
	• clear status transitions
	• a meaningful drag-and-drop workflow board
Example workflow states:
	• New
	• Assessing
	• Monitoring
	• Escalated
	• Resolved
What should be implemented
The implemented proof of concept can include:
	• JavaFX UI
	• incident board with drag-and-drop
	• incident details
	• passenger list
	• support role handling
	• base-station takeover
	• business rules for escalation
	• logging of actions
	• mock data
	• JUnit tests for key logic
What can be mocked
The following may be mocked or simulated:
	• real AI diagnosis
	• real medical sensors
	• real flight suit telemetry
	• real spacecraft systems
	• real network communication
	• real external databases if not necessary
	• advanced analytics
Technical expectation for the code
The code should:
	• be written in Java
	• preferably use Maven
	• use JavaFX
	• follow a clean layered structure
	• separate UI logic from business logic
	• avoid giant classes
	• use interfaces where appropriate
	• be easy to explain in a presentation
	• be realistic for a student proof of concept
Deliverables our team should support
We need material for:
	• runnable prototype
	• technical documentation
	• architecture explanation
	• BPMN process model
	• personas
	• scope description
	• UI overview / mockups
	• user manual
	• final presentation demo
Scope boundary
We are not building a complete space tourism enterprise platform.
We are building a focused proof of concept for one core process in the Space Flight phase only.
Whenever there is a choice, the solution should prefer:
	• clarity
	• maintainability
	• presentation value
	• realistic scope
over excessive complexity.

